European inflation has slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying rise in food prices.
The price increase in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 per cent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent, the Luxembourg-based Statistical Office of the Union announced.
Official forecasts gave as likely as only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest rate, under the pretext that the decline, coupled with rising commodity prices and the reduction of forced unemployment, would provoke a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the trap of 22: "it has to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene later on on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the record of twelve years; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation spiked in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat futures prices rose by 88 percent, and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching last month the black gold almost $ 100 per barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will already fall to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months at around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double interest rates during 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while the Gallup had never before experienced such a low level – 13 percent – in the case of the Socialists.
The difference in the case of the safe voters of the parties – due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters – would mean a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) versus a support of one-fifth for the socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the limit necessary to have some parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is one two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation particularly bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
With regard to next year, the majority of the population is seeing the situation deteriorate and only one-tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of respondents, higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the Prime Minister is performing poorly rather than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány a lot, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population do not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced towards the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent felt it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, today this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believes that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation answered that they would participate safely and another 20 percent said that they are likely to participate.
By comparison, only 55 percent of the population would participate in "a general election to be held this Sunday" and another 15 percent believes their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters, there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of paying tuition fees, 79 percent of medical consultations and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The Budaörs gold trading triangle hypermarkets maintained the average price level rise of 16 percent, with the difference that VAT has not increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also saw an average 16 percent increase in Budaörs’ gold trading triangle, Napi’s usual Christmas basket, but in all hypermarkets growth was well above HUF 1,000.
As in December last year prices in supermarkets had already “shooted”, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers the fact that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they can not do it even for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003, that basket cost HUF 6800.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data from the Central Statistical Office, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the Coca-Cola with a two-liter bottle cost less than HUF 200, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only HUF 257.
However, in the basket of Napi Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year’s average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during last year’s Christmas in prices there was an increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, the supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the trader misses the speed of circulation of a product, he may lose a significant profit in the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF to the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only a 844 HUF.
Such extremes did not occur this year, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased by 1284 HUF.
Compared to the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets more than 30 percent increased the price of essential consumer goods.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the Central Statistical Office figures: this office, in the case of some basic foods, recorded a price increase of more than 30 percent over the 12-month interval.
So, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, since in the price of this product, which was quite expensive last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all indices, suppliers of flour are in a stronger position than those of egg, being able to impose the dramatic increase in prices even to multinationals.
Hypermarkets don’t complain about the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our collected experiences, most consumers of the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, carrying by pallets the preserved foods.
In the morning of Wednesday, the three stores formed large queues in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that domestic sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, hospitals have reported several thousand infections caused primarily by the improper application of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
A wounded man in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after had to return to the hospital as a result of MRSA infection and since then it has not been possible to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacterium in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been safely recorded in hospitals, and no information is available.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-produced infections (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is applied excessively or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, turn into highly resistant bacteria to antibiotics, and quickly become infected in inappropriate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicemia, primarily to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened organism, to the elderly or to people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the Hospital János there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are everyday in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, nurses serve them in rubber gloves and masks, and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment,” Nyulasi said.
Hospitalized patients are screened in advance for the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection cannot be prevented in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospitalized MRSA infections in most cases, but current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and transmission of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA in their bodies.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not fashionable.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to the public when MRSA infections already occur visible in the patient - said the doctor-head of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes rigorous commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for treating infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of outpatients or in basic care," said Karolina Böröcz.
Saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare staff.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but also in this sense there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is contagious through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, you can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation you save with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In Karolina Böröcz's opinion, where appropriate preventive measures are taken, there are fewer infections of this type or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
