The British Army recruits on YouTube
The units of the British Army in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operations corps, then sent to London for upload to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers that have been uploaded to the Internet in this way and its "channel" has already been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of actions perpetrated in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Category: Operations in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to present to the public the true purpose of the British army’s presence abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs virtually nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example, about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, somewhat hypocritical, the officers talk about maximum losses, but do not present the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have been uploaded to the Internet already numerous videos recorded in real operations, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with free downloadable shooter video games, called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers.
