The party is not always written with red numbers.
In Hungary, the law precisely defines the days that are written in red numbers on the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - which next year will be less - workdays are reorganized.
Even in the EU or North America, the holidays are not unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holidays, state holidays and public holidays.
The festive days are mainly related to religious festivals and historical ephemerals.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive - the latter above all so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven parties written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15, commemorating the revolution of 1848 and on October 23, commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the State, on May 1st the feast of labor, on November 1st and 2nd we commemorate our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, in our country are two-day feasts Easter of Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it often becomes a bridge when before or after the holiday there is only one working day.
In exchange for the weekends so long, during the previous Saturdays you can not be absent from work or school.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when you have to work exactly in exchange for the day directly before or after the feast.
This legal norm is compulsory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not compulsory, however, for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work uninterrupted even during holidays.
This year the order of work can be altered only around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country is practically stopped, since according to experience, most people "do bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
The agenda will first be modified around the work party so that workers can then rest for four consecutive days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so in return Friday May 2 will be a holiday.
The other change relates to the holiday of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, you will have to work instead of Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, the year that comes during the holiday of the end of the year can rest, since from December 24 will not work almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six small deterrents to bitter the lives of your colleagues
Emails that we forget to send, audio messages that we never receive, innocent lies that pass on to us without realizing: all of them are part of our everyday Folklore at work.
You have to decide whether to adapt to the little inconveniences or consciously avoid the confusing situations that can irritate others.
Advice.
I'm sorry, I forgot to let you know you've been picked up by the marketing department," says one of your colleagues.
Is that why you didn't go on a date?
At best, she feels it and tries to fix the issue, probably calling the marketing department to tell them that she forgot to deliver the message (this is the less common solution).
Most of the time the issue is solved by apologies.
Before proceeding to lazy explanations, it is worthwhile to meditate on the things you can make your colleagues’ lives bitter and consciously strive to avoid them.
Do you borrow something that is not yours?
There’s nothing more annoying than when you want to grab a document, an office utility, or your phone and you don’t find it.
Remember yesterday you put the stapler on the table, but for this morning it disappeared?
Do you find your lost pen on the desk of one of your colleagues?
Do not take anything away from your colleagues without asking them, because they will rightly be angry with you for stealing their things.
Do not pick up envelopes or post-it from the office because it may be unpleasant when you need them immediately and they run out of time.
Gossip about your colleagues' private lives?
There is no good solution to stop rumours that are already running.
Who, what is he doing and with whom?
Where and why?
Do not pass on to everyone the information (suppositions) you have about the particular life of your colleagues!
Do not abuse the trust of your colleague when he shares with you his most intimate secrets!
Bury in yourself what you have heard and do not gossip about your colleague in his absence, even if others also know the things about him.
Are you going on sick leave unjustifiably?
When you call the office on the phone and say you are sick and your head hurts unbearably, you feel bad or you feel that day you prefer to rest; think about what others have to do your work, your impossibly tasks, your work by term.
Don't bother your colleague!
If you already know in advance that the next day you will not go to the office or something may happen to you, so you will have to stay at home, communicate to them, so that your colleagues or your boss do not have to face your absence the next day.
Tarareos, laughter, phone calls
Are you involved in your work, but are you suddenly getting rid of the laughter of your colleagues?
Have you involuntarily heard a phone conversation that would have been better not to hear it?
Don’t bother your colleagues with your tarareas, chants, conversations aloud (less when you do them above their heads), slanders, constant blasphemies, expressing your discontent aloud.
All of these can be annoying, even if they are not deepening at this time in a project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for a mistake?
Don’t blame others if you haven’t finished something in time, you’ve forgotten to send an important letter or message!
Do not allude to the eventually reigning chaos in the office, nor to the noise your colleagues make!
You must recognize if you have made a mistake that harms others and you must correct the mistake!
Ask how you can fix your mistake!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Jogging and slippers: very comfortable habit for the house, but not suitable for the office!
Don’t wear comfortable jogging even if your occupation allows it!
Don’t be messy, respect your colleagues and yourself by wearing everyday clothes, elegant and beautiful when your occupation so demands!
