The U.S. Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
More than a hundred billion dollars will be received in the Monetary Marking through tenders.
In these tenders, banks auction the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the US Fed will bid forty billion dollars, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the 9/11 attacks, it is the first time central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step must solve the biggest economic problem, that is, the continued growth of the free capital shortage that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report for customers.
“This coordinated action by central banks probably reduced the recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent sixty billion dollars on unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
“Central banks must really be afraid of what awaits them yet when they decided to take this step,” said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems with access to loans and will therefore have to lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the global economy.
The central banks thus decided, after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, London interbank rate used for the loan of money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend money even when the U.S., Canada and Britain central banks cut their interest rates several times during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as another drop in interest rates," Tempus Consulting's Greg Salvaggio told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the move by central banks contributes to igniting the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem that is the fall of the U.S. real estate market.
