A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archive documents, stored over 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not yet accessible only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or their rightholders.
The eleven States in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective from yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches to be made " particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced labour ", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of certain deportation victims.
The records of concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, eventually, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents,” Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Center on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, said in 2006.
