The Scottish NHS needs to monitor criminal records of employees outside Europe, a watchdog said.
The recommendation of Auditor General Robert Black came after it was verified that a foreign doctor was related to the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also showed his concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea of the amount of foreign personnel it has.
However, his report pointed out other controls that are carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor-general checked the amount of foreign personnel hired outside the European Economic Area, following the attacks on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after colliding with a jeep at the gates of the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who acted at Old Bailey by video conferencing in October, charged in connection with the alleged car bombings in the UK.
The NHS hopes to conduct pre-employment checks on candidates, to ensure they meet the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although Scotland’s health board uses “Disclosure Scotland” to carry out criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report recommends, among other measures, that the boards should have the guidance of the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal checks in many countries outside Britain.
“Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review,” the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: “Our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the number of NHS foreign personnel.”
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
“The report suggests that pre-employment checks work at NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is,” he explained.
Scottish health authorities say there are currently 1,161 foreigners, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying employees with indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures established by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being complied with widely.
This includes passport controls, work permits and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing the foreigners’ pre-employment policy and guide in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I had a great interest in this work being carried out in the wake of the terrorist attack at Glasgow airport.
He added that the Scottish government, together with health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in updating the pre-employment control guidelines for all working groups – including foreigners – what they planned to publish next month.
