Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been proposed until now. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlwinds at the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
For the past three decades, researchers have suspected that there could be rays on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, rays are silent from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous Urey-Miller life origin model, rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it's not like that: if there was ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Possibly, Venus is a "diabolical" twin from Earth, but it remains a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since since the 1990s there have been no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of research that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, in the opinion of the researchers, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more characteristics in common with Earth than we had previously assumed," ESA said in a statement.
Despite the well-known stormy winds in the North Pole, the researchers also discovered in the southern polar region a vortex formed by the clouds that spins faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the Earth’s poles, as described by a team of Giuseppe Piccioni researchers from the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet is also called a dawn star or evening star orbiting the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus, with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar, does not resemble Earth much, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets, water had agglomerated that remained on Earth in the oceans, but on Venus it was dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
